<<Upload Packer (Compressor)>>

The [Upload Packer] is used to compress the mail@4006
packets which are to be uploaded <<TO>> the
Server (Boss). The packer is an external programme
which compresses data prior to transfer and is more
commonly known as an archiver. It is advisable to use
a packer but not absolutely necessary.

For a start, you could get PKZIP, LHA, ARJ or RAR.
<<(Confirm this with your Sysop.)>>

If you use one of these (or other well known ones),
XP gives you a simple pick-list (<F2>) and all
the parameters are pre-entered.

Just make sure that the packer .EXE file is where
CrossPoint can find it. If in doubt, just put it in
the CrossPoint directory but the DOS path will do
also.

The following macros are available, which are
replaced by CrossPoint at the right time
with the correct values.


<<$UPFILE>> the name of the compressed file.
        (is fixed because the transfer protocol
        also has to use it).


<<$PUFFER>> the file that is to be compressed.
        (the outgoing mail packet created by
         CrossPoint).

Make sure XP can find the Packer (in the current
directory, DOS PATH (see DOS handbook) or enter the
full path name). All parameters are entered for
you. XP even <<beeps>> to warn you if, when you exit the
dialog box, it cannot find the packer.

If you do not know which [packer] to use, ask your@4006
Sysop!

<<Unpacked Transfer (Z-Netz)
It may be worthwhile sending unpacked data, if your
modem can pack it (MNP5 or V42bis). This saves above
all on-line time, because the server only packs when
you call, and you have to wait while it packs.

MNP5 or V42bis are not so good as packers, so it
needs to be checked with care. Does the time saved
through not waiting for the packer make up for the
time lost through less effective packing?

You can pack for upload and not for download, but the
difference for usual small upload is insignificant.

Some boxes allow this unpacked service (not all, ask
your Sysop)

In this case, just use "copy" instead of a packer!

copy $PUFFER $UPFILE

<<unpacked transfer (MausNet)
See above Z-Netz, but as above with "COPY"

