8000
A (very) few Fido boxes require the point password,
to be sent additionally inside the poll packet you
send (as a so-called "session password"). Activating
this switch will cause that to happen.

Your Sysop will tell you if it is necessary or not.
@
8001
In some of the [Fido compatible nets] points use a@4009
[node address] instead of a point address. If this@4010
is the case, you must set this switch, and put the
*node number* in the space for the point number.
If your server has the number 12:345/67, and you have
been allocated the node number 89, then your address
is 12:345/89. Your *node* number is 89.
@
8002
Some Fido servers give problems, in that they only
send you something, when they actually receive some-
thing from you. If you haven't any mails to send, you
would get nothing. Why this problem exists is one of
life's great mysteries, but this switch gets round
it, whatever the cause. It causes a packet to be
sent with effectively nothing in it.

In *rare* cases that can cause problems of its own,
when the box software doesn't know what to do with
an empty packet, but that, dear reader, is another
story...
@
8003
Incoming Fido message packets normally have a file
extension made out of the day of the week plus a
number, eg. *.MO3 or *.TU1.

But not all. For example some boxes now put a letter
on instead of a number (*.MOA).

If you should be served by a box that sends files
with different names from "standard", you must
activate this switch, so that packets with non
standard names are imported. Your Sysop can tell
you what to expect from his box.

This means of course, that XP cannot recognise
files which really are other types so easily, so for
example a file with extension MOD, that is not a mail
packet, lands in the SPOOL subdirectory and not in
your file request directory as it otherwise would.
(All mail packets go temporarily to SPOOL to be
worked on)

@
8005
Enter your two digit Point number here.
@
8006
This is the name used during the Log On to start the
netcall module in the box. Here should nearly always
<<NET410>> be entered.

Some QuickMail boxes (a German net) offer extra
features which can be called up using other names
here. Ask your Sysop about this.
@
8010
This is the packet size that CrossPoint suggests to
the called system. The bigger the packet size, the
faster the data transfer rate.

Many incomplete UUCP implementations have diffi-
culties with larger packets, sometimes even above
128 bytes, and break off the connection. In such
cases you have to set CrossPoint to small packet
sizes here.

CrossPoint can always adapt itself to the other
side and supports all possible packet sizes from
64 up to 4096 bytes.
@
8011
This is the so-called "UUCP Window" size. This
decides how many packets will be sent before the
sending system waits for an acknowledgement.

Possible window sizes are 3 to 7. Normally the
setting 7 works fine, and speeds things up.
@
8012
A UUCP-g connection usually tries to send packets
always of the same size. This is however inefficient
especially with small quantities of data.

Better UUCP systems are able to work with variable
packet sizes, which helps efficiency, but above all
is the only way that works with HST Modems.
If in doubt you just have to try whether the transfer
works with variable packet sizes.

CrossPoint adapts itself to whatever packet size the
other side sends, and can work with any size mixture.
@
8013
<<[ ]>> ->  CrossPoint uses the packet size as
        requested by the called system.

<<[x]>> ->  The packet size as set above will be
        used for sending and receiving, regardless.

In cases where the received packet is significantly
bigger than that sent (eg. 1024 against 64 bytes),
the transfer rate can sometimes be increased by
raising and fixing the size of the send packet
with this switch. It depends also on the system at
the other end, whether this works.
@
8014
<<[x]>> ->  CrossPoint offers the called system a
        "size negotiation". This means that each
        informs the other of the file size each time
        before it is transferred. This gives for
        example a more meaningful display on the
        screen during the transfer.
"Size Negotiation" is not supported by all UUCP
systems, but it does not normally lead to problems,
since the called system can simply ignore it.
@
8015
For setting which of the UUCP transfer protocols
offered by the called system will be accepted by
CrossPoint.

If all or more than one is marked to use, CrossPoint
has preferences. If all are marked, CrossPoint will
use UUCP-g over UUCP-e if offered. If you wish to
force UUCP-e, you must switch off UUCP-g.

<<UUCP-g>>  This is a standard protocol that all
        UUCP systems support. It offers a fairly
        error free transfer, but is very slow
        for small size [data packets]@8010


<<UUCP-G>>  This is a slightly improved version of
        UUCP-g, which enables on some systems the
        use of [variable size] data packets.@8012

<<UUCP-z>>  This is a non standard protocol, but is
        offered by many German UUCP systems. It
        offers a high transfer rate together with
        adequate error control and is very suitable
        for modem links which already have an error
        correction through MNP5 or V.42.

<<UUCP-f>>  This is only suitable for transfer of
        *unpacked* data across links with MNP5 or
        V.42 error correction. Use it only when
        UUCP-g is too slow, and UUCP-z is not
        available.

<<UUCP-e>>  This gives very good transfer rates, but
        offers no error control. It is only suitable
        for modems offering error correction like
        MNP5 or V.42 when in addition data loss at
        the serial port (also of the called system!)
        is certain not to happen.

        Do not use under multitasking environments
        like Windows!

@
8016
CrossPoint announces itself to the called system with
this name. If nothing else has been agreed, this is
the same as your System Name or Point Name.
@
8017
<<[x]>> ->  When "on" your Mails (PMs) will be sent
        via "Batched SMTP" (AKA BSMTP). This means
        instead of sending each message as a separate
        file, they are bundled together as a package,
        which raises the transfer rate considerably.

Not all UUCP systems support this, so if in doubt
ask your systems operator.
