Some UUCP systems exchange data at Log-In with
"even parity". Suffice it to say here, if your
system operator tells you to use "7/e/1" or "E/7/1"
or something like "7 bit with even parity", you
should activate this switch.
@
160
CrossPoint waits this many seconds after sending the
command to dial to receive a "connect" answer. After
this time CrossPoint breaks off, and starts waiting
for the next try.

Note: many Modems also have such a setting, often
set to 60 seconds as default. That is probably what
is happening if the call is aborted sooner than you
expect. Check your modem handbook about increasing
this value if you need to (often "S Registers")
@
161
CrossPoint waits this many seconds after the
"connect" message, to obtain a successful Log-In.

If this time expires, XP hangs up and waits for the
next try.

Note: These cost money, since the other side
answered the phone! You can set the number of
these attempts separately in another box here,
[Max. Connects],to limit costs@166
@
162
CrossPoint waits this many seconds after an aborted
netcall attempt, before trying again.
@
163
This sets the number of times CrossPoint will try to
call a number if it does not achieve a successful
netcall, at intervals set by Dial Pause.

Since some boxes are often engaged (busy), it may be
necessary to set 20 or 30 attempts here, set at
perhaps 90 seconds intervals (too frequently is
not recommended).

You can protect against disaster if the other side
should answer every time and you get billed for 30
useless call, by setting "max. connects" separately.

If the number of tries has been made without
success, CrossPoint stops trying and carries on
with the next programmed activity, if any, or
returns to the CrossPoint screen.
@
164
This limits the number of attempts <<during one
<<connect>> that CrossPoint will make to log on.
Not to be confused with the setting for
"max. connects".

After this number of tries, CrossPoint gives up, and
waits for the next dialling attempt.

If the Log-In does not work with 2 or 3 attempts
(repeat, when the phone gets answered, not engaged
tones or no answer) there is something wrong.

If you do not know exactly that your side is working
correctly, check that your Point Name and password
are entered correctly.
You may find a clue by starting CrossPoint with the
/d switch (debug), which shows you more of what is
happening at Log-In, and try looking in the file
ERRORS.LOG, where errors are recorded.

Otherwise, maybe the server has a problem, wait a
while, maybe it gets fixed, or call your system
operator (Sysop) for help.

@
165
After a successfully log on, the server starts to
gather the data together to send to you, and to
[pack it]. Especially if there is a lot, this can@4006
take some minutes. You can set a time limit in
seconds here, to prevent CrossPoint waiting all
night on the phone if something does go wrong, but
be fairly generous here; 10 minutes (600 seconds)
should be enough for a "normal" user, but if you have
a slow server (286er or something) or a lot of data,
it can be more.

You should observe your netcalls sometimes, to see
how long is usual.

<<NOTE>> Some modems have a setting to abort after a
certain time if no data is transferred (inactivity
timeout), again to protect the user from high phone
bills. This must obviously be set slightly higher
than CrossPoint's limit. If the call gets aborted
before the CrossPoint timer reaches 00:00, this may
be the cause. Check your modem handbook.

@
166
Limits the number of tries where a connect happens
but goes wrong.

There are 2 types of failed netcall attempt:

o  There was no connection; the box was busy
   or didn't answer. This is annoying, but
   doesn't cost anything.

o  There was a connection, the box answered the
   phone, but something went wrong after that.
   These cost money, so you don't want CrossPoint
   making one of these for every one of a possibly
   large number of attempts you have allowed for
   when the box is busy.

Here you can limit separately the number of attempts
when a connect happens. Obviously CrossPoint must
then break off attempts to reach this box this
session, so as not to risk another failed connect.

For example, if you set "max Connects" to 3, and
"max. dialling attempts" to 50, CrossPoint will try
up to 50 times as long as the phone is not answered,
but will give up directly after the third time that
a connect happened without a successful netcall.

@
167
The figure you enter here determines the minimum
cps rate for Zmodem transfers. If the transfer drops
below this figure for two minutes, the transfer will
be aborted.

A setting of <<0>> disables this feature!

@
168
You can enter a default setting for resetting
your modem (see modem handbook about resetting,
or initialising) under the menu /Config/Modem.

If you need different settings for different
servers, you can enter them here.

The default reset will sent first, then the box
specific settings <<additionally>>.

Note: like the dialling command, you have to prefix
this command line with "AT" (or whatever your modem
needs, but they are nearly all AT

If you wish to send a <Enter> to the modem, you can
put a "\\" in the line. After this a new AT will be
necessary before carrying on. eg. ATE1\\ATS13=32.
This is usually not necessary, all the commands can
strung together after one AT, but occasionally a
modem will prefer a <Enter> after certain commands
before it accepts it properly.

@
169
The COM Port number to which the modem to be used
for dialling the selected box is connected.
Ports COM1 to COM4 are supported.

This selects the COM Port to be used, whereas under
/Config/Modem/COMx the ports in general are set up.

Also make sure that the port settings, to be found
under menu /Config/Modem/Com(x), are correct.
Especially using COM3 and COM4 can be tricky, and
proper IRQ numbers and port addresses are essential
(see On-Line Help there).
@
170
This is for setting the port speed, "baud rate"
"DTE speed" or "DTE rate", the bit rate for data
transfer between modem and computer. This speed can,
but must not be the same as the bit rate, as
achieved by the connect, the "link rate", across
the telephone line.

This setting can be tricky, because it is must also
be set at the modem end of this cable. Most modems
do this automatically, but if they are set to adjust
it later automatically to the "link rate", it may
become different, leading to problems.
It is best to set the modem to "hold DTE rate"
and not adjust (see modem handbook).

Modems which can compress data (MNP5, V.42) send
less data out over the telephone than they get from
the computer, so the link computer<->modem (DTE rate)
must be faster than the modem "connect" (link rate).

As a rule,
pure 2400bps modem, DTE rate also 2400.
2400 modem with MNP5 or V.42, DTE rate 9600.
9600-14400 modem, DTE rate 19200
above 14400 modem, DTE rate 38800.

Note 1: your modem may report at Connect
either the link rate or the DTE rate (or both).
You can often adjust this, see modem handbook.

Note 2: Older and slower PC, XT and AT will
almost certainly have difficulty with settings
above 19200 without a [FIFO 16550 UART].@4011
Also faster but multitasking 386 and up will have
problems above 19200 without a 16550.

In general, except for the most basic system,
a [16550 Chip] is to be recommended, and the@4011
switch to activate it can be found under
/Config/Modem.

A selection can be made from a list of the usual
port settings by pressing <F2>, but any sensible
value can be entered manually, eg. 4800.
Any value is allowed, that the serial interface
supports.
Stick to the standard ones, though.

@
180
Enter here the number of seconds a telephone unit
gives when calling this server (depends whether it
is local or long distance) both for cheap rate
and normal rate, and how much 100 units costs.
Get these values from your phone book.

Also enter the time it usually takes for this server
between answering the phone and the "connect"
message.  This is to calculate charges correctly.
CrossPoint cannot know when the phone is picked up,
and you start paying. It can only start timing from
the "connect", so it adds this time to connect when
calculating the phone charges.

Time it by turning on the modem's loudspeaker and
timing between the click when the other side picks up
and when the "CD" (Carrier Detect) lamp on the modem
lights up.
The time is between 5 and about 15 seconds usually.

