296
<<[+]>>     Ignore state of CD (carrier detect).

Most modems indicate a correct connect by switching
the CD line "high" and lighting the CD light on the
modem. CrossPoint detects this and can reliably
determine that a connect has been detected.

If, however, your modem does *not* normally send this
signal for some reason, or maybe your modem cable is
not so good, XP would normally disconnect because CD
is "low".

This switch causes XP to carry on, regardless of the
state of CD.

Note: CD provides information for XP and if XP has
to get by without it, errors could occur which would
otherwise be recognised.
You should attempt to get the CD recognition to work.

For Fido Netcalls, the CD function <<MUST>> work
correctly anyway.

@
297
<<[+]>>     Ignore state of CTS (Clear To Send).

The modem switches the CTS line to show the local
computer that it is ready to receive data from it
(the modem is clear for the PC to send).

If this signal is not possible, probably because the
wire in the cable is not connected (as is the case
with some cheap cables), setting this switch will
bypass it and tell CrossPoint and the PC to send data
when *it* wants to, regardless of what the modem may
be doing.

Note: especially with slow rates (up to 2400bps),
this missing signal can lead to characters sent to
the modem getting lost, with unpredictable results.
You should attempt to get the CTS to work.

