A FOSSIL driver is a TSR program which, under DOS,
takes over the job of controlling the ComPort,
leaving an application programme less work to do.

Since they take over the job of controlling the Port,
IRQs, Addresses, [16550 UARTs] and so on, all these@4011
options are switched out of CrossPoint if this option
is set.

For normal modems, XP has its own Port driver which
is just as good as any Fossil, so leave this option
off. Especially under OS/2, you should leave it off.

You only need to use it if you wish XP to talk with
something exotic, like an ISDN card, a serial port
on another network machine or if you are experiencing
problems with throughput and/or CRC errors.

Tried and tested DOS fossil drivers include X00,
BNU and ADF.

