490
You can enter up to 3 external coding programs,
linked in to CrossPoint through the pmCrypt system.
The entries are as follows:

<<Name:>>
The name of the coding process. It is only a
description for you, it is not used.

<<Encode:>>
The name (call) of a program (or batch file) which
will ENcode a file (put it into code). CrossPoint
will put the message to be encoded as the temporary
file CRYPT.MSG (in the TEMP directory). The result of
the actions of the called program must leave a
(coded) file CRYPT.ENC in the same directory.

The following macros can be used to pass information
to the program:

<<$INFILE>>   =  <TempDir>\CRYPT.MSG
<<$OUTFILE>>  =  <TempDir>\CRYPT.ENC
<<$KEY>>      =  the code key (Password)
<<$USER>>     =  Name of the recipient of the coded
                 message

<TempDir> stands for the directory you entered under
/Config/Paths as the temporary directory.

<<Decode:>>
The name (call) of a program (or batch file) which
will DEcode a file. CrossPoint will put the message
to be decoded as the temporary file CRYPT.ENC (in the
TEMP directory). The result of the actions of the
called program must leave a (decoded) file CRYPT.MSG
in the same directory.

<<$INFILE>>   =  <TempDir>\CRYPT.ENC
<<$OUTFILE>>  =  <TempDir>\CRYPT.MSG
<<$USER>>     =  Name of the sender of the coded
                 message


<<binary  [x]:>>
This switch sets the result of the coding operation
to be send as a binary file (like sending other files
as binary messages).

[ ] sends a text file as a normal message.

Since the encoded messages are not formatted like
text, this switch should normally be set to send them
as binary files.

ONLY set this switch off, if you can (and wish to)
produce a proper ASCII text file from the encoding
procedure.

This can be useful, because some nets do not allow
binary files, and they must be converted to ASCII
files in a special form. The net will probably do
this, but you can avoid extra work for the net.

PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) can do this for example
with the switch -a)

þ XP will check the message and set it to binary
  anyway, if it contains non-text characters.

þ If the recipient uses THE ANSWER or another point
  program which *requires* the binary form when
  receiving messages for the pmCrypt system, so you
  must also use binary for sending.

<<Example 1:>>

Let us suppose you wish to use a (fictitious) program
called SUPERKEY, which has the following syntax:

encoding: SUPERKEY <Source> <Result> <Key> code
decoding: SUPERKEY <Source> <Result> <Key> dec

Then enter the following:

Name:       SUPERKEY
Encode: SUPERKEY $INFILE $OUTFILE $KEY code
Decode: SUPERKEY $INFILE $OUTFILE $KEY dec

<<Example 2:>>

PC-DES (the internal XP cipher) expects the password
to be entered from the keyboard. A trick using the
DOS echo command achieves that when PC-DES is set up
to run under pmCrypt.

Name:       PC-DES
Codierer:   echo $KEY|PC-DES $INFILE
Decodierer: echo $KEY|PC-DES $INFILE

The program is not called, it is XP internal anyway,
but this activates it automatically and feeds it the
password.

