<<PM>>

A "PM" is a private mail, sometimes called net mail.
As opposed to a message written to a public newsgroup
for everyone to read, it goes only to one (or more)
recipients selected by you.

If you write a PM reply to a message in a newsgroup
XP sends that reply automatically only to the person
who wrote the message.

When replying to a PM, of course, you can only write
a PM. (P or Ctrl-P or shift-P).

Trying to write with Ctrl-R or R will give an error
message.

PMs written to a person are stored in Newsgroups
in the [User Overview] (TAB from the normal@21
Newsgroup overview). Press <Enter> on the User
Name, and you will see messages, if present.

@
4001
<<  Newsgroup (NG)

A Newsgroup is simply one of a large collection of
"places" where messages are written publicly, for
anyone to read, on a specific subject specified
by the title of the Newsgroup.

In FidoNet, Newsgroups are known as Echomail Areas.

The NGs are listed in the Newsgroup overview
window in CrossPoint, showing their titles, which
is a good indicator as to what subject they cover.

To get Newsgroups, you have to [subscribe]@10308
(menu /message/Newsmanager) to them, that is, order
them from whatever source you intend to get your
NGs from.

@
4002
<<Sending complete Files>>

Instead of writing your text into the editor
directly, you may want to send a file which is
already on your disk.

You can send Text Files, which the reader can
read just as if it were a message, or you can
send Binary Files (Program Files for example)
which are treated in a different way, to prevent
them being corrupted.

You must send binary files as binary.

XP will ask you for a path and name to the file you
want to send. Give it, and XP will either copy into
your SEND directory, or, depending on the
[Binary Limit] set in /Config/Options/Messages@240
just note the path to it for later.

When the next netcall is made, XP will send the file
just like any other message.

