4005
<<Transfer Protocol

<< You need a Transfer Program in addition to XP!

A Transfer Protocol is a kind of code system by which
data are transferred across a modem link. For the
link to work, both sides have to understand this
protocol.
Examples of protocols are Z-Modem, X-Modem, BiModem,
but there are many others.

These protocols are not to be confused with the
programs which can carry them out. There are for
example many programs which can "do" Z-Modem, and
as long as each side has one of these (not
necessarily the same one), the link works.

Many terminal programs have "built in protocols"
and you don't notice when they are being called.

CrossPoint does not have it's own protocol (except
in FIDO, which is special), but calls a separate
program (<<which you must of course have>>, in addition
to CrossPoint) to do the work. This is more flexible.

When CrossPoint has caused the modem to call the
server, it makes a Log On using the data (passwords)
and so on which you entered, and tells the server
which Point is calling, so the server knows to ready
the packet in your point (pigeonhole) to send, and to
receive a (possibly empty) packet from you.

When this point is reached, the server hands over to
a <<transfer program>>, telling it to *receive* a
file. This program readies itself. At the same time
(because it's an agreed system), CrossPoint knows it
has to send a file, your mail packet. Even if you
have no mail to send, it sends a dummy packet.
CrossPoint also calls up an external program, and
this indicates to the other side that it wants to
send. They understand each other, because they
"speak" the same protocol, the transfer is made and
ended.
The same (or other, if you really want) programs are
immediately called again, this time for the server
to send and your side to receive.

If they don't understand each other for any reason
(wrong program, wrong parameters), an error occurs
and they break off.

This is why you must agree with your sysop beforehand
which protocol is to be used.

Make sure the program you are going to use is in a
path (PATH: see DOS handbook) where XP can find it.
XP even beeps to warn you if, when you exit the
dialog box, it cannot "see" the program you entered.

In the server set-up, you have to enter the correct
parameters for whatever program you are using
(XP pre enters them for the most common ones, if
you use something exotic, see its handbook), once for
the upload where you *send*, and once for the
download, where you *receive*.

@
4006
<<Packers

Packers are programs external to CrossPoint, which
compress the data before transfer, or decompress it
after transfer (the server does the same).

This compression really reduces the quantity of
data to be transferred, and saves a lot of time
and money.

The packer is called in a similar way to the
[transfer program], but before the transfer.@4005

<< You need a packer>>, and so that both sides can
unpack what the other side packed, it needs to be
agreed beforehand between you and your sysop, which
packer will be used.

There are others that you can learn about with
experience, but the only ones worth bothering
about at the start are:
ARJ
LHA
PKZIP and its unpacker PKUNZIP

ARJ is *free* for private use, packs well, is fast
and well known these days for DOS. It is not used
on other [platforms] (Amiga etc.), but agree it with@4007
your sysop if you can.

LHA is also free, is good but not quite so fast and
does not pack quite so well as ARJ. It is very well
known and used on all platforms.

PKZIP/PKUNZIP are very good, also available for all
[platforms] but for DOS it is shareware and you@4007
should pay for it (other platforms have it free).

These programs are known to XP, and as long as
XP can find them (in the current directory,
DOS PATH (see DOS handbook), or give the enter
the full path name), all parameters are entered
for you. XP even beeps to warn you if, when you
exit the dialog box, it cannot "see" the packer.

The packer has to be called, telling it what file
to pack and what to name the result, or which file
to unpack (the name of the result is already in the
packed file). This is all entered automatically for
the packers known to CrossPoint.

@
4007
<<Platform

Basically the type of Operating System, as MS-DOS
is to the PC. OS/2 is another "platform", as is
Unix (Unix on different types of computer is only
one platform!), Amigas or Ataris with their operating
systems are different platforms, etc.

The subject becomes important in Data Exchange,
because your Modem can get a connect and exchange
data with a a modem on a completely different type
of machine.

Text Files are the same all over, but just because
you can pack with ARJ, doesn't mean that ARJ is
available to him to unpack. There may be no ARJ for
a Cray supercomputer, no matter how fast it is.

