4009
<<AKA & FIDO-compatible Networks,
(AKA =  Also Known As)

There are many Networks which are based on the same
software and technology as FIDO but are separate
from FIDO. These Networks have addresses for their
Points which are similar to, but different from, the
"real" FIDO. Many Fido systems carry these other
Networks in addition to Fido but they are separate
Networks. If you have one or more of these
"alternative" addresses (or Points) in these other
Networks, then, as well as your main Fido address,
you will need to send your "Also Known As" (AKA)
because when you make your Netcall, you want to be
able to get and send the mail packets for these other
Networks at the same time.

If you poll with [EMSI], you can do this. It does not@158
work with YooHoo.

If you list your AKA's in your main Fido Server entry
in CrossPoint, CrossPoint will know that it also has
to collect and send mail packets for these addresses.
The packets are kept separate for the different Nets.

<<Setting up AKAs
First, you simply set up the addresses for these Nets
each under its own Server, (see /Edit/Servers) where
they are all identical to your main Fido Server,
except the Node address is different.

You do <<NOT>> need to call these Servers, they just
serve as the correct gathering point for messages for
these Nets.

CrossPoint can then keep the Areas coming from these
Nets separate and send your replies and messages into
the correct Net. The areas are then automatically
allocated to the correct Net. Just be careful, if you
should add an Area by hand, to make sure you allocate
it to the correct Server for that Net.

Then enter these other addresses in your main Fido
Server in the appropriate boxes "AKA" and "Send
packets for".

Remember, it only works with EMSI and when
CrossPoint makes a Netcall to your main server, it
includes Netcall operations for these AKAs at the
same time.

Example:
Your main Fido address is 2:245/678.15
Your BossNode is 2:245/678 and you are Point 15.

You participate in 2 other Nets on this Server as
9:111/222.15   and
987:1/15 (a small Net where all [Points are Nodes])@8001

Set up 3 identical servers, except with the 3
different addresses, leaving "AKA" and "send packets
for" empty.
For 987:1/15 set the switch "use node address"

In the main server, set under "select" <<main Fido
<<server>> ON.

In this server enter in "AKA"
9:111/222.15 987:1/15 (separated by a <space>)

and "send packets for"
9:111/222 987:1/0
Note that here the point number is left off, and in
the small net "0" is used

@
4010
<< Fido Addresses, Nodes and Points

Points are addresses which are only indirectly on the
net. They can only call up their particular server to
collect their messages, and deliver messages to be
sent on by that server. Mail can only be sent to them
care of their server.

A "true" Fido box is directly on the net, and must be
capable of being called directly by other boxes to
deliver and collect mail. These type of boxes are
called nodes, or hubs, and have addresses of the form
2:555/666. This means in the world area 2, they are
in the  sub area 555, and the node number 666 in that
sub area. Servers are of course this type of box.

Points are just extensions to a node, and have an
extra number on the node number, after a point, as
address, e.g. 2:555/666.24 (24 is the point number).

Points do not have the same rights and capabilities
in Fido as nodes.

In some of the [Fido compatible nets], especially where@4009
the numbers are small, all participants are raised to
the status of nodes, with a node address, even if
other nodes cannot call them direct.

@
4011
<< UARTs, 16550, FIFO

The normal serial port of a PC is equipped with a
serial I/O chip called a UART. Older PC's may be
fitted with a 16450 UART. This version basically gets
the bits, as they come from the modem, makes a byte,
tells the CPU (by means of a so-called interrupt)
that it is there and holds each one for the CPU to
fetch, one at a time. If the CPU, for some reason,
doesn't pick it up in time, it gets over-written by
the next one and data is lost.

Although it's hard to believe, the CPU is so fast
that most of the time, it gets it. But older, slower
computers do have problems at/over 19200bps.

Faster computers, like the 486 and 586 manage better
but not infinitely better and especially so long
as they are not doing anything else, like
multitasking. Under Windows or OS/2 even fast
computers can get into trouble and "drop" bytes.

You observe this as drastically reduced transfer
rates, block re-sends and so on.

Fortunately, there is a simple and fairly cheap
solution: the 16550 FIFO UART.

This has quite simply a 16 byte (yes, just 16 bytes)
buffer. Therefore, the computer only needs to go get
bytes one sixteenth (a bit sooner to be safe) as
often. (FIFO just means First In First Out and is
not relevant to our explanation)

The good part is that this thing is directly pin
compatible to the 16450 one. You pull the old one
out and put the new one in. It costs about $10.

You just need a (normal) serial interface card
(COM Port) where the 16450 chips are in sockets
and can be removed, get one of these 16550 (most
electronics shops have them now that they are in
demand), and plug it in <<the right way round>>.

<<NOTE:>>.There are various versions with similar
numbers, not all quite so good. Get one from
National Semiconductor with 16550AN or 16550AFN
(the N is important here!) on them. Some non-
original versions are not recognised properly by
CrossPoint.

There are of course more exotic versions, special
adapter cards, etc., but research into these is left
to the reader.

@
4012
<<Re:

It is usual in some nets to preface the (original)
subject with "Re:" when replying to a message.

Some people take this to be an abbreviation of
"Reply" or even "reference", but it throws back
to older days of business letter writing, where,
from the Latin, it meant "on the subject of:"
and was the customary form for saying what you were
writing about, in particular for referring to
previous correspondence, hence its use in e-mail.

A new subject is written without "Re:", a reply with.

Not all nets like it though, so be careful. MausNet
does not use it at all, UseNet uses only a simple,
single "Re:". CrossPoint deals with Maus and UseNet
for you, you do not have to set it specially.
Fido is undecided, but it is mostly NOT used.
Z-Netz prefers the "Re^n" form to "Re:Re:Re:".

Many e-mail programs add this "Re:" automatically,
simply sticking it on the front. This can however
lead to long chains of "Re:Re:Re:", and not much room
for the actual subject. Some people think this ugly
and wasteful, and it is common now for programs to
gather up all the "Re:" present, count them, add 1
and produce a summary "Re^n", eg. Re^3, indicating
this is the third level of reply.

CrossPoint offers most possibilities:

a) Gather up the Re:'s to Re^n
b) Just put a Re: on the front, regardless
c) Add no Re:, and even remove any Re: present

There are 2 places this can be set:

1. /Config/Options/Messages for a default setting.
   Here however you can only decide between a) & b)
   above.

2. /Edit/Groups/Edit under "Replies" for the setting
   for that particular group, overriding the default.
   Here you can decide between a), b) & c) above.

@
4013
<<Quote character:

It is usual to mark text that you have quoted from
a previous message with a special character at the
beginning of each line, to show that it's quoted.

This is usually the ">" character. Many programmes
recognise this and can treat quoted text specially,
just as XP can: it can highlight it in a different
colour for clarity and even count the quantity.

Bearing this in mind, in CrossPoint you can use
what you like but remember, you may be quoting text
that is already itself quoted and if it is
complicated, other readers will not be able to follow
who quoted what. Remember that people simply do not
read what they cannot easily follow.

Stick to the ">" character.

@
4014
<<Reference Links>>

A particular subject as it threads its way day by day
with more and more replies through the mass of other
messages builds a so called "thread". Some threads
are small, but some are *very* extensive, with many
branches, and even changes of subject text.

Sometimes it happens that you stumble across a
message that is interesting, but you need to read
the rest of the discussion to understand what is
going on. Otherwise you may write something that
someone else already wrote, or out of context
for example.

Some nets like FIDO and Maus, UseNet and ZCONNECT
(the newer Z-Netz format) link replies to messages
by using and placing information in the header about
which thread the message belongs to.

<<This is called "reference linking" a thread.

In this way messages belonging to the same thread can
be gathered together to be read all at once. (Using
the subject text alone is not unreliable. You will
miss a branch of the thread if the subject changes).

XP asks if you want to keep the link if you change
the subject in a reply to a message.

CrossPoint notes all these "reference links" when a
netcall is imported and has them ready if you want to
see them.

You can see the links, if present, to any message by
pressing "\#". If there are none, it just tells you.

<Alt-B> does a similar function, but the unreliable
way using the subject text, and has to search all
messages every time.

