<<AUTOEXEC Directory and Operation

CrossPoint actions files in the AUTOEXEC directory
automatically, at every XP start-up. It also does
this about every 5 minutes (if you are in the main
window and have not pressed a key for 30 seconds).
You can also do this manually by setting a function
key or tool (/Config/Keys or /Config/Tools Menu)
with only "*" for the program and the <<"AutoExec"
switch ON.

CrossPoint actions the file according to the file
extension.

 .ZER  A puffer file in ZCONNECT (Z-Netz) format, it
       is imported, then deleted. The front part of
       the file tells XP which server it comes from,
       eg. HIT.ZER will be imported as coming from
       the server HIT (see EBEST.* below)

 .ZEE  As ZER but sends receipt acknowledgements
       as requested in messages (see EBEST.* below).

 .OUT  A MausTausch-Outfile. It is converted (with
       MAGGI.EXE) to ZCONNECT format, imported and
       deleted. As for ZER, the file name tells XP
       the server name.

 .PKT  Fido-PKT-File. As .OUT converted with
       ZFIDO.EXE. In this case your Fido Boss Node is
       always used as server.

 .MSG  A message file or other file to be sent
       (see below).

 .MSD  As MSG, but is deleted after being sent.

 .IPS  A pre-prepared ZConnect Puffer File. The front
       part of the file name tells XP which server to
       send it to (HIT.IPS sends it to the HIT). (It
       must of course be one of your servers)
       See also parameter /ips below.

 .PAR  A parameter file, with each line a CrossPoint
       [start parameter] which is sent to XP when it@4020
       starts up, just as though it had been entered
       on the command line.
       Is deleted after use.

 .OPT  Just like .PAR, but is NOT deleted.

 .BAT  Any normal batch file. The following special
       batch files have special functions:

        START.BAT  run every time XP is started.
        START1.BAT run at the next start-up of XP,
                   then deleted.
        STOP.BAT   run every time XP is ended.
        STOP1.BAT  run the next time XP is ended then
                   deleted.

All other batch files are <<deleted>> after they have
been run.

 .BAK  The file is simply deleted.

Do not put any other files in the AutoExec directory.

<<Control files for .ZER .OUT & .PKT files

The presence of so-called control files activates
various options for these message-packets as they are
imported. Only the file name is important, not the
contents.
These files have the ending .CTD (deleted after use)
or .CTL (NOT deleted after use)

 EBEST.CTL/.CTD   Sends  receipt confirmations for
                  those messages which have requests
                  for it in them.

 EDATUM.CTL/.CTD  Sets the receipt date of received
                  messages to the date of writing of
                  the message.

 GELESEN.CTL/.CTD Sets the messages straight to
                  "already read".


<<Message Files .MSG/.MSD

    Files to be sent as messages should have the
    following format, to enable the header to be
    produced correctly:

        To:  USER@ADDRESS, /NEWSGROUP or [cc List]
        Subject:     (the usual subject line)
        Server:      (Box name)

        Message Text starts here


   ================================================

The "Server" line may be left empty, in which case XP
either finds the correct server for the recipient or
sends it to your main server.

Note: If you send to a Newsgroup, it must also exist
in your newsgroup list, otherwise it will NOT be
sent.

To send Binary Files put in an extra line:

        To:  USER@ADDRESS, /NEWSGROUP or [cc List]
        Subject:     (the usual subject line)
        Server:      (Box name)
        File:    c:\path\file

For anything other than Fido File-Attaches, any text
entered in the body of the message is ignored and
will not be sent. If you do not enter the full path,
but only the name, the file must be in the SEND
directory, as defined under /Config/Paths.

For Fido File-Attaches you must use the .MSG ending,
otherwise the attach-file is deleted before the Fido
mailer can transfer it. For Fido it is obligatory to
enter the "server" line.

If you integrate an external program which sends
messages through the AUTOEXEC directory, then you
should set the AUTOEXEC switch in the set-up window
for either the /Config/Tools or the Config/Keys.
This runs the AUTOEXEC routine each time this program
is finished.

<<AUTOEXEC in Timing-Lists

You can put the command AUTOEXEC (also selectable
with <F2>) in a timing list, to run the AutoExec
routine at a fixed time.
<<It will also be run when the date changes.

START batch files will not be run in this case.

<<Notes
Order of events at CrossPoint start-up.

 1. Read in AutoExec ".OPT" parameter files
 2. Read in command line [parameters].@4020
 3. Read in AutoExec ".PAR" parameter files.
 4. Send AutoSend messages (/Config/AutoSend)
 5. .ZER .ZEE .OUT .PKT files imported.
 6. .IPS .MSG .MSD messages sent
 7. START1.BAT run
 8. START.BAT run
 9. /user Option evaluated (set Username)
10. /ip & /ips puffers sent/imported
11. /n & /t parameters run (start netcalls)
12. /r & /pack parameters run (re-org & pack)
13. /k command run (macro)

