4021
  þ Netcall vanished?  ERROR.LOG
If an error occurs during a netcall or some other
automatic function, CrossPoint shows the error
message for a few minutes then carries on. This
prevents a whole series of unrelated tasks being
aborted by one error. To enable tracking down the
errors, CrossPoint writes all error messages into a
file <<ERRORS.LOG>>, and often what action it took,
like renaming files for safety. Always look in this
file if you think something has gone wrong.

(Note: There are other useful LOG files too!)

Normally, especially according to the Zerberus
standard in Z-Netz, if a netcall goes wrong, both
sides should recognise this, delete what has been
transferred and keep each keep the original netcall
packets to re-send next time.

Unfortunately this is not 100% reliable. BiModem for
example has caused puffer loss.

Setting the (rename CALLED) switch under
/Config/Options/Netcall renames a received CALLED
file for safety even after an interrupted netcall.
So, if the data do not get sent again, you can try to
rescue something. It is also useful if something
(very rarely, eg., power cut) goes wrong after the
file has been correctly received, while being
imported.

