4022
<< Netcall automatic and Timing Lists.

Here is an example of a program list. Each line
represents one activity, and defines times when
it will be carried out.

 + 22:00-22:59  01.01.-31.12.  þþþþþþþ  NETCALL HIT
   22:20-23:59  01.01.-31.12.  þ þ þþ   NETCALL JOKL
 + 00:05-01:30  01.01.-31.12.  þ  þ     REORG
 + 01:45-01:46  01.01.-31.12.  þþþþþþþ  EXEC doit.bat
 + 03:00-03:00  10.12.-10.12.  þþþþþþþ  QUIT

The entries have the following meaning:
 + 22:00-22:59  01.01.-31.12.  þþþþþþþ  NETCALL HIT
 ³ ³            ³              ³        ³
 ³ ³            ³              ³        À Activity
 ³ ³            ³              À Weekdays (Mon-Sun)
 ³ ³            ÀÄÄ Dated period for the activity
 ³ ÀÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ Time period
 ÀÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ + = shows it is active

The "+" means that the entry is active, ie. will be
carried out. Toggle active on and off with "A".

The first entry is the start and stop <<time>> for the
activity, ie. the period during which the activity
will be attempted. For example 10:00 to 11:59 for a
netcall will mean CrossPoint starts attempting a
netcall at 10:00, and if not successful, will give up
at 11:59.

If it is successful earlier, it stops anyway and does
no more in this period.

The end time may be before the start time, in which
case CrossPoint will make 2 activities out of it.
 "11:00-10:00" would be handled as:
 "00:00-10:00" and "11:00-23:59".

The next entry is a start and stop <<date>> for the
activity. The activity will not be attempted before
the start date or after the end date. During this
period, behavior will be regulated by the weekday
entry and the time-of-day entries.

Next is a pattern symbolising the weekdays you have
entered on which the activity should be carried out.

Finally the command is shown for the activity to be
carried out. The following commands are available:

<<NETCALL BOX>>  Netcall at "BOX"

<<REORG>>        Re-organise data bank
                 (as /Re-Org/Messages

<<PACK>>         Pack Data Bank
                 (as /Re-Org pack)

<<EXEC Prog.>>   Start Program or Batch file

<<END>>          Stop running the Timing List
<<QUIT>>         End the program
<<QUIT n>>       End the program with Errorlevel n
<<QUIT_ONCE>>    End the program, but only once in
                 the time period.
<<QUIT_ONCE n>>  ditto, but with Errorlevel n

<<AUTOEXEC>>     Action entries in the AUTOEXEC
                 directory.
<<CRASH z:n/n>>  Fido-Crash at node z:n/n
<<CRASHS>>       Do all waiting crashes
<<REQUESTS>>     Do all waiting File-Requests

